ars will be given with\never sale of shirts, $1 and up, at\nIsrael's, until further notice. it\nC. C. Davidson has gone to E\nPaso to attend the Y. M. C. A.\nconvention.\nJ. M. Hodges, the county com\nty commissioner, spent Wednesday\nin the city.\nTwo collars will be given with\nevery sale of shirts, $1 and up, at\nIsrael's until further notice. it\nClint Ratherford has moved in\nto the new location opposite the\nNews building. This is a splendid\nlocation, and Clint should have an\nincrease in business.\nTwo collars will be given with\nevery sale of shirts, $1 and up, at\nIsrael's, until further notice. it\nMulaney, who is to have charge\nof the play circuit for this district\nwhen the Heman opera is finished,\nhas gone to Chicago to purchase\ncurtain, scenery, etc.\nMrs. C. W. Barker, an experienc\ned dress maker, has rooms at the\nStreet residence. All work guaran\nteed. Prices reasonable. Phone 65\n22 tf\nFor up to date dress making, see\nMrs. C. W. Barker. Satisfaction\nguaranteed. Phone 65. 22 tf\nMiss Maud Reed held the lucky\ncoupon of 15c tickets and received\nthe beautiful black bear rug. How\nell Moore received the silver watch.\nRemember the St. Patrick's ball,\ngiven by Professor and Mrs. Fra\nzier, at the skating rink, cn the 17th\nof Ireland.\nC. T. Adair is under way with\nhis new meat market and has all\nkinds of fresh meats. The butcher\nis Owen of Ft. Worth, Texas, who\nhas been in the employ of Swift\nCo.\nThe tennis court of the South\nwestern clerks seems to be a popu\nlar place for the lovers of that\ngame. Almost every afternoon finds\na party of enthusiastic players\nthere.\nCelebrated Hammer Paint at\nChapman's, saves 25 per cent.\n22-it\nThe pri.es to be given next Mon\nday night at the Crystal Theater\ncan be seen in the window of the\nNew York Cut Price store. 22 it\nWe are informed that Mr. Israel,\nwho is in a hospital in Chicago,\nwhere he was recently operated on\nfor appendicitis is slowly recover\ning, but will necessarily have to re\nmain there for some time yet.\nChapman sells Diamond edge\ntools and cutlery, 22-it\nThe Crystal Amusement Co. will\nopen in their new theater, on Cen\nter street, between 2d and 3d, just\neast of the skating rink, next Mon\nday night, March 9th. 22 2t\nWANTED Light housekeeping\nsuite, close in on east side. Ad\ndress P. Box 601. 21 tf\nSTRAYED One chestnut sor\nrel horse, about 134 hands high;\nfresh cut in wire branded VL on\nleft thigh. Owner can get the ani\nmal by paying for this advertise\nment and cost of keeping. J. S.\nMontano, Revuelto, N. M. 21 tf\nH. D. Welch of the Welch hard\nware Co., El Paso, was in town a\nday or two this week and was\ngreatly pleased with the business\noutlook. \"This,\" he said, \"is a\nbusiness community, isn't it?\"\nA city firm hung out a sign,\nBoy Wanted.\" In less than five\nminutes a redheaded little chap\nstepped into the office with the\nsign under his arm. ''Say,\nmister,\" he said \"did you hang\nthis out?\" ,'1 did,\" said the\nproprietor. \"Why did you tear it\ndown?\" back of his freckles the\nboy gazed in wonder at the man's\nstupiditv. \"Why,\" he replied,\n\"I'm the boy.\" And he proved to\nbe.\nNotice To Taxpayers.\nI the undersigned, assessor of\nthe county\" of Santa Fe, Territory\nof New Mexico, hereby give notice\nto all persons owners of taxable\nproperty, real or personal in the\ncounty, that under the law they\nare required to file schedules of\ntheir property with the assessor on\nthe first day of March, 1908, or\nthereafter until the 30th day of\nApril, 1908. I will be at my office\nat the court house to furnish blank\ntax schedules, to receive schedules,\nand to administer the oath required\nby law. I will also give due\nnotice of visits to precints outside\nof the city for the purpose of tak\ning reports of assessments. Blank\nschedules, will be furnished on ap\nplication by mail to property own\ners. Dated Tucumcari, New Mexico,\nthis the 7th day of March 1908.\nSam Ciiadwick,\n22 tf County Assessor.\nThe Wednesday night dance giv\nen by the club was as usual a very\nenjoyable affair. The club is grow\ning very fast, and seems to fill a\n\"long felt want\" in this line. Next\nweek's dance will be on Thursday\ninstead of Wednesday, the club\ncourteously giving way for the Re\nbckahs, who are preparing a play\nto be presented soon.\nDr. II D. Nichols, surgeon for\nthe railways of this city and who\nhas been in the hospital at Ala\nmogordo for the past six weeks\nunder treatment for inffammatory\nrheumatism, has gone to Hot\nSprings, Ark., where he hopes to\nget relief. Mrs. Nichols and the\nbaby are with him. His many\nfriends here certainly hope to see\nhis speedy recovery.\n1 GET READY\nfor the FAIR! 1\nSeeds Buy grown Seeds, best\nvarieties for New Mexico. Try\nthem. One package each. Win\nter Watermelon, Winter Musk\nmelon, Okra, Sandwich Island\nPumpkin, Lettuce, Red Seeded\nCitron, Radish, Pie Pumpkin,\nMixed Melons, Sunflower, Summer\nSquash, Cream Peas, Winter\nSquash, Seeded Ribbon Cane,\nPop Corn, Japanese Millet. All\npostpaid for 50 cents; worth 1.00.\nAny 7 packages, 25c. Send money\norder to\nHERSCHEL JONES,\nL. B. No. 5. Logan, N. N.\nI\nCOLLEGE men are said to be the smartest,\nmost critical dressers and that's one reason why\nHart Schaffner Marx\n1\n1\nclothes are so very popular in college towns. These clothes\nare not made for college men only; if you never went to\ncollege that's no reason why you can't dress in style.\nWe're ready to show you or any other man the best\nclothes ever seen in this town; they're Hart Schaffner\nMarx clothes; all-wool fabrics, perfectly tailored, accurate\nin style, correct in fit.\nBest money's worth of clothes you ever saw. We can\nshow you suits in many styles from $18, $20, $25, $30\nup to $45.\nOUR STORE 15 THE HOME OF\nHART SCHAFFNER MARX CLOTHES\nAND OTHER GUARANTEED QOODS.\nI\nHancock\ntint!\nmem\ngrowing,\n1\nBlock.\nTAFOYA LAWSON\nCopyright 1908 by\nHart Schaffner Mar\nThe Store\nof Quality.\n1","height":"29152","width":"20268"}}
